<p>HUMAN RIGHTS COUNCIL 
Eighth session 
Agenda item 1 
</p>
<p><b>ORGANIZATIONAL AND PROCEDURAL MATTERS 
</b></p>
<p><b>Cuba, Egypt (on behalf of the African Group), India, Russian Federation, 
Singapore</b>*<b>, Sri Lanka:  draft decision 
</b></p>
<p><b>8/...  Appointment of special procedures mandate-holders 
</b></p>
<p> The Human Rights Council, with regard to the appointment of thematic special procedures 
mandate-holders, decided that: 
</p>
<p> (<i>a</i>) All mandate-holders, on completion of their first term of three years, would require 
reappointment for the second term of three years by the Council; 
</p>
<p> (<i>b</i>) The Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights would 
prepare and circulate a list of mandate-holders due for reappointment at least three months prior 
to the completion of their first term; 
</p>
<p> (<i>c</i>) Any Member State(s) may bring to the attention of the President objections that they 
may have regarding any special procedures mandate-holders, indicating the basis of their 
objections; 
</p>
<p>                                                 
</p>
<p>*<b>  </b>Non-member State of the Human Rights Council. </p>

 <p></p>
<p> (<i>d</i>) Upon receipt of any objections, the President shall hold consultations with the 
concerned Member State(s) and regional coordinators with the aim of reaching a consensus; 
consultations may be held with other stakeholders if deemed necessary; 
</p>
<p> (<i>e</i>) In the event that no agreement is reached, the Council shall make an appropriate 
decision; 
</p>
<p> (<i>f</i>) In all other cases of special procedures mandate-holders who have completed three 
years and about whom no objections have been expressed, the President may recommend 
renewal of their mandates for another three-year term to the Council for approval. </p>
